<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-03-11T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-03-11T06:00:00-05:00" n="48" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d48">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">894.00/1009: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-11T20:00:00+09:00">March 11,
                                    1941—8 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received March 11—3:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>390. 1. There are increasing indications that a reorganization of the
                            Cabinet is under discussion in high quarters.…</p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                        <p>6. I now attempt no assessment of the effects of these trends and
                            possible changes on foreign problems. I would certainly not expect to
                            see any marked modification of Japan’s objectives nor indeed of her
                            outward manifestations of attitude, but recent developments here
                            together with available indices of future trends, some of which have
                            arisen from American military preparations, point in the main toward
                            decrease of the will further to aggravate Japan’s international
                            difficulties and toward an increase of caution.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>